                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d971">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/3124.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.—Extracts.—Paraphrases.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-10T11:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 10, 1912—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The injunctions contained in the second paragraph of the Department’s March 9, 7
                    p.m., have already been carried out in precisely the manner suggested. An
                    international organization will be perfected as soon as possible. A
                    representative committee has been formed, which will take no step, either in
                    policy or action, except after consultation with me, and I shall only permit
                    them the most unquestionably correct procedure. The British, German, Spanish,
                    French, and Italian colonies and the Mexico City Chamber of Commerce are
                    organizing.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
